\chapter{Assessment of Intrinsic Small Signal Parameters}

%%
\section{Introduction}

SiC MESFETs offer large breakdown field, high saturation velocity, and high thermal conductivity \cite{Hjelmgren2007,Song2004}. They can operate at high biasing voltages and have high thermal robustness with large output resistance relative to other semiconductor devices, such as GaAs MESFETs \cite{Gang2010,Elahipanah2010,Clarke2002}. SiC MESFETs exhibit stable thermal performance, i.e. only 10\% change in their characteristics is observed when operated at 500$^\circ$C \cite{Spry2004}. They offer the highest absolute power density due to large breakdown voltage \cite{Deng2011,Xiao2013,Weitzel1995}. Therefore, SiC MESFETs are very attractive for high power microwave applications, such as transmitters for communication and RADAR.

SiC MESFETs used in RF applications have been reported in the literature.  Song et al. \cite{Song2004} fabricated 4H-SiC MESFETs on a conducting SiC substrate and measurements showed that unity current gain frequency, $f_T$ = 3.2GHz, maximum frequency of oscillation, $f_{max}$ = 12.4GHz, an RF power gain of 5.9dB, and a maximum output power of 25.3dBm (0.85 W/mm) at 2GHz, which is much higher than Si and GaAs equivalent size transistors.

It is an established fact that  RF performance of a MESFET depends on its gate length, $L_g$ and saturation velocity, $\upsilon_s$ of its carriers. In general, with reduction in $L_g$, the value of $f_T$ increases. However, when $L_g$ is less than 1$\mu$m, the device suffers from short channel effects and performance of the device is degraded \cite{Yim2011}, which includes: reduction in transconductance, $g_m$; shift in threshold voltage, $V_T$ and increase in the device output conductance, $g_d$ \cite{Honda2003}.

Additionally, in short channel devices, vertical electric field becomes stronger to an extent that even at smaller values of $V_{ds}$, the mobility, $\mu_0$ of the carriers starts to reduce. Ho-Young et al. \cite{Cha2005}, in their study of transport characteristics of short channel SiC MESFETs, reported that $\upsilon_s$ and $\mu_0$ of such devices are 1.7$\times$10$^7$ cm/s and 300 cm$^2$(Vs)$^{-1}$ respectively, which are smaller than those of earlier reported values.

Another important short channel effect is the drain induced barrier lowering (DIBL), causing less gate control on the channel current, $I_{ds}$ thus, increasing $g_d$ and decreasing $g_m$ of the device. Further, at high $V_{ds}$, the flow of carriers can also divert towards the substrate resulting in large substrate current. Honda \cite{Honda2003} and Manabu \cite{Arai2003} in their investigation of short channel effects, demonstrated that when $L_g$ is less than 1 $\mu$m, gate loses its effective control over $I_{ds}$ due to DIBL. They also reported that $f_T$, power density, and $g_m$ start to saturate at $ L_g\sim$ 0.3$\mu$m. $f_T$ of a SiC MESFET is given by \cite{Orouji2011,Ladbrooke1989}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.1}
f_{T} \approx \left[\frac{g_{m}}{2\pi(C_{gs}+C_{gd})}\right]~,
\end{equation}
where, $C_{gs}$ is gate-to-source capacitance and $C_{gd}$, is gate-to-drain capacitance defined as \cite{Ladbrooke1989}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.2}
C_{gs} \approx \left[\frac{\varepsilon_sWL_g}{h_0}\right]\left[1+\frac{X}{2L_g}-\frac{2h_0}{L_g+2X}\right]~.
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.3}
C_{gd} \approx \left[\frac{2\varepsilon_sW}{1+2X/L_g}\right]~.
\end{equation}
$X$ represents extension of gate depletion layer towards the drain-side of the gate and is given by \cite{Ladbrooke1989}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.4}
X \approx \sqrt{\left[\frac{2\varepsilon_s}{qN_d(-V_{gs}+V_{bi})}\right]}(V_{ds}-V_{gs}+V_{bi})~,
\end{equation}
and $h_0$ of Eq. \ref{Eq:5.2} is given by
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.5}
h_0 = \sqrt{\frac{2\varepsilon_s(-V_{gs}+V_{bi})}{qN_d}}~.
\end{equation}
In above expressions, $\varepsilon_s$ represents permittivity of SiC material, $V_{gs}$ is gate-to-source biasing, $V_{bi}$ is the built-in potential, $W$ represents width of the device, $q$ is the electronic charge and $N_d$ channel doping density. Theoretical value of $g_m$, after considering the reduction in $\upsilon_s$, because of the transverse electric field, is defined as \cite{Ladbrooke1989}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.6}
g_m = \frac{\varepsilon_s\upsilon_sW}{3h_0}~.
\end{equation}
Transconductance delay, $\tau$ is given by
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.7}
\tau \approx \frac{1}{\upsilon_s}\left[\frac{X}{2}-\frac{2h_0}{1+2X/L_g}\right]~.
\end{equation}
Channel resistance, $R_i$ after the onset of current saturation is defined as
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.8}
R_i = \left[\frac{\upsilon_sL_g}{\mu I_{ch}}\right]~,
\end{equation}
where $I_{ch}$ is given by
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.9}
I_{ch} = qN_d\upsilon_s[a-h(x)]W~,
\end{equation}
where $a$ represents epi-layer thickness and $h(x)$ is given by
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.10}
h(x) = \sqrt{\frac{2\varepsilon_s(V_{ds}-V_{gs}+V_{bi})}{qN_d}}~.
\end{equation}
Since there is non uniformity in $h(x)$ underneath the Schottky barrier gate caused by the applied voltage $V_{ds}$, which generates $C_{ds}$ capacitor thus, by assuming that the depletion layer involved in the definition of $C_{ds}$ is $h(x)/2$ and also because of submicron geometry, the shape of depletion tends to become circular. And it can safely be assumed that one quarter of a circle under $L_g$ is involved in defining $C_{ds}$ thus, \cite{Ahmed2003, Riaz2016}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.11}
C_{ds} \approx \left[\frac{W\varepsilon_sh(x)/2}{L_g/4}\right]~.
\end{equation}
And output conductance, $g_{d}$ can be approximated as \cite{Ladbrooke1989}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.11a}
g_{d}\approx\frac{I_{ch}}{4V_{ds}}~.
\end{equation}
Eqns. \ref{Eq:5.2} to \ref{Eq:5.11a} represent intrinsic small signal elements, here onward referred to as conventional technique to assess intrinsic small signal parameters of a SiC MESFET \cite{Ladbrooke1989}. These parameters are, primarily, responsible for determining high frequency and high power characteristics of the device. As evident from Eqns. \ref{Eq:5.2} to \ref{Eq:5.11a}, intrinsic small signal parameters are material, biasing and device design dependent. Effects of source and drain parasitic resistances, $R_S$ and $R_D$ can be incorporated by using
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.11c}
R_{S}= \frac{L_{sg}}{qN\mu aW}+R_C~~\text{and} ~~R_{D}= \frac{L_{dg}}{qN\mu aW}+R_C~,
\end{equation}
where $L_{sg}$ and $L_{dg}$ are the source-to-gate and gate-to-source separations, and $R_C$ is ohmic contact resistance, typically $2\Omega$ for microwave devices. Thus, effective $V_{dse}$ is evaluated using either $V_{dse}=V_{ds}-I_{ch}(R_S+R_D)$, or $V_{dse}=V_{ds}-I_{ch}(R_S)$, whichever is applicable.

It is an established fact that SiC MESFETs are meant for high biasing and high temperature related applications where conventional approach to assess intrinsic small signal parameters may not be fully valid. At high biasing, there are considerable self-heating effects inside the device, which make the carriers hot and their scattering probability into the buffer and Schottky barrier layers increase. Expressions involved in the conventional technique are, primarily, dependent on gate depletion layer thus, any modification in depletion layer thickness because of high temperature/biasing is bound to generate errors in the assessed values of these parameters.

In this chapter, a technique has been developed to assess the intrinsic small signal parameters of submicron SiC MESFETs by involving experimental $I-V$ characteristics. The developed technique takes into account possible depletion layer modification due to high temperature/biasing and is capable of predicting AC small signal parameters to an acceptable accuracy. The remaining part of the paper consists of development of a proposed technique for the assessment of small signal parameters for submicron SiC MESFETs. Followed by its comparison with experimental data and also with the conventional approach. The dependence of small signal parameters on the device biasing has been discussed at the end, using a MATLAB based simulation process.

\section{Model Development}
A crossectional view of a SiC MESFET is shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:5.1a}. It has $n$-channel doping of 2.7$\times$10$^{17}$cm$^{-3}$ grown on a buffer layer having a $p$-doping of 5$\times$10$^{15}$cm$^{-3}$ as shown in Table \ref{Tab:5.1}. It is an interdigitated device having total gate periphery of 2$\times200\mu$m \cite{Hjelmgren2007}. Device to device isolation is achieved by mesa etching whereas, drain-source leakage is controlled by a fully depleted buffer grown on a semi-insulating substrate.

Fundamental difference in the proposed and the conventional technique is that $I_{ch}$ of the conventional approach is changed with $I_{ds}$, which is evaluated using expression \cite{Riaz2016}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.12}
\begin{split}
I_{ds}=&I_{dss} \left(1-\frac{\delta V_{gs}}{V_T+\Delta V_T+\gamma V_{ds}}\right)^2\\
\\
&\times \left(1+\lambda V_{ds}+\frac{\delta V_{gs}}{V_{ds(sat)}}\right) \tanh(\alpha V_{ds})~,
\end{split}
\end{equation}

\begin{figure}
\centering
%\includegraphics [scale=0.5]{3D}
\includegraphics [width=3in, height=2.5in]{ThesisFigs/Fig5_1a.pdf}
\caption{Crossectional view of a SiC MESFET.}
\label{Fig:5.1a}
\end{figure}

where $\delta$ represents non-ideality in Schottky barrier of a SiC MESFET, $\Delta V_T$ corresponds to shift in $V_T$ because of submicron geometry, $\gamma$ simulates $V_T$ dependence on $V_{ds}$, $\lambda$ takes care of finite output conductance in the saturation region of operation, $\alpha$ defines the slope of the linear region, $I_{dss}$ represents drain-to-source current at $V_{gs}=0$V and saturation knee voltage is represented by $V_{ds(sat)}$. The output impedance of the MESFET has been taken care of by the term $\lambda V_{ds}$. A relatively high value of $\lambda$ would mean that the device has high output conductance as a function of $V_{ds}$, resultantly its output impedance will be relatively low. Differentiating Eq. \ref{Eq:5.12} with respect to $V_{gs}$ and $V_{ds}$, one will have
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.12b}
g_{m}=\frac{\partial I_{ds}}{\partial V_{gs}}\bigg|_{V_{ds-const}}~.
\end{equation}
Also
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.12c}
g_{d}=\frac{\partial I_{ds}}{\partial V_{ds}}\bigg|_{V_{gs-const}}~.
\end{equation}

Reason for changing $I_{ch}$ with $I_{ds}$ is that in short channel devices, especially at elevated temperatures and biasing, there could be a possible modification in the Schottky barrier depletion layer due to increased occupancy of high energy states by the energetic carriers. Such a modified depletion layer can be assessed to a reasonable accuracy by knowing $I_{ds}$ having dependance on  available channel crossection, i.e. $a-h(x)$ as shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:5.1a}. Following this concept, expressions based on $h(x)$ can be modified, such as gate-to-source capacitance, $C_{gsm}$ can be redefined as \cite{Ahmed2003}

\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.13}
C_{gsm} \approx (\varepsilon_sWL_g)\left[a-\frac{I_{ds}}{qN_d\upsilon_sW}\right]^{-1}~.
\end{equation}

While developing Eq. \ref{Eq:5.13}, it has been assumed that because of submicron geometry, carriers are attaining saturation velocity in a close vicinity of the source side of the gate electrode hence, saturation current has been used in Eq. \ref{Eq:5.13}. Extending the logic of parallel plate capacitor gate-to-drain capacitance, $C_{gdm}$ follows an expression of the form defined by Eq. \ref{Eq:5.14a} \cite{Ladbrooke1989}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.14a}
C_{gdm} =\dfrac{\varepsilon_sW}{\bigg(1+\dfrac{2X}{L_g}\bigg)}~.
\end{equation}
But in submicron devices, depletion underneath the Schottky barrier becomes circular and its extension in such cases towards the drain side can be assumed as identical in all directions thus, $X\approx h(x)$. Therefore, Eq. \ref{Eq:5.14a} can be written as
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.14b}
C_{gdm} =\dfrac{\varepsilon_sW}{\bigg(1+\dfrac{2h(x)}{L_g}\bigg)}~.
\end{equation}
From Eq. \ref{Eq:5.9}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.14c}
h(x)=\bigg[a-\dfrac{I_{ds}}{qN_d \upsilon_s W}\bigg]~.
\end{equation}
By combining Eq. \ref{Eq:5.14b} and \ref{Eq:5.14c} and rearranging, we get
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.14}
C_{gdm} \approx \left[\frac{\varepsilon_sW}{1+(2/L_g)\bigg[a-\biggl(I_{ds}/{qN_d\upsilon_sW}\biggr)\bigg]}\right]~.
\end{equation}

Drain-to-source capacitance, $C_{dsm}$ of a SiC MESFET is defined by the non-uniform depletion layer distribution underneath the Schottky barrier gate of the device. Thus, separation between the two layers of charges defining $C_{dsm}$ capacitor will be determined by length $L_g$ of the device. Considering quarter circle approximation because of the submission geometry \cite{Riaz2016}, the capacitor $C_{dsm}$ can be expressed as
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.15}
C_{dsm} \approx \left[\frac{2W\varepsilon_s\biggl\{a-\biggl(I_{ds}/{qN_d\upsilon_sW}\biggr)\biggr\}}{L_g/4}\right]~.
\end{equation}
Using Eqns. \ref{Eq:5.14} and \ref{Eq:5.15}, modified unity gain frequency, $f_T$ is defined as

\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.16}
f_{T1} \approx \left[\frac{g_{mm}}{2\pi(C_{gsm}+C_{gdm})}\right]~,
\end{equation}
where $g_{mm}$ is given by

\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.17a}
g_{mm} = (g_{m0})e^{-j\omega \tau_m}
\end{equation}
such that $g_{m0}$ can be attained by differentiating Eq. \ref{Eq:5.12} with respect to $V_{gs}$, keeping $V_{ds}$ constant \cite{Memon2007}. Transconductance delay, $\tau_m$ is defined as

\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.18}
\tau_m \approx\biggl[ \frac{C_{gsm}+C_{gd1}}{2g_{mm}}\biggr]~.
\end{equation}
In Eq. \ref{Eq:5.18}, a factor of two is used to adjust the depletion modification caused by high electric field. Since the device under discussion, by using its physical parameters given in Table \ref{Tab:5.1}, should pinch-off at $V_{gs}$ = -5.6V by considering both $V_T$ and $\triangle V_T$ \cite{Ahmed1995}. Since the observed pinch-off, as evident from Fig. \ref{Fig:5.1}, is much higher than the calculated value because of self-heating effects, a factor of 2 is used to accommodate low $g_m$, which is a direct consequence of high $V_T$.

Channel resistance, $R_{im}$ is given by Eq. \ref{Eq:5.19}

\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.19}
R_{im} = \left[\frac{\upsilon_sL_g}{\mu I_{ds}}\right]~.
\end{equation}
Since in a distributed network where a current path is modelled by a combination of multiple series resistors and parallel capacitors as offered by the MESFET channel with respect to its gate metal, the magnitude of the current decreases progressively while travelling through the channel hence, offering a non-uniform resistance. Therefore, an AC resistance, in principle, would be less than its DC counterpart \cite{Ladbrooke1989}, which for a submicron device can be assumed as one half of the DC resistance, thus, output conductance, $g_{dm}$ can be approximated as,

\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.20}
g_{dm}\approx \frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial I_{ds}}{\partial V_{ds}}\bigg|_{V_{gs(cont)}}~,
\end{equation}
where $I_{ds}$ is given by Eq. \ref{Eq:5.12}. In summary, Eqs. \ref{Eq:5.12} to \ref{Eq:5.20} define a proposed set of expressions to estimate intrinsic small signal elements of microwave SiC MESFETs.

\section{Measured and Simulated DC Characteristics}

To check the validity of the proposed model and to compare it with experimental data, a MATLAB code has been developed involving swarm optimization technique wherein, Eq. \ref{Eq:5.12} has been implemented \cite{Riaz2016}. A submicron SiC MESFET is chosen \cite{Hjelmgren2007} whose details are given in Table \ref{Tab:5.1}. Wherein, buffer layer thickness is represented by, $b$ and its doping density with variable, $N_b$. It is worth mentioning that buffer layer depletion, $x_P$, evaluated using Eq. \ref{Eq:5.21}, has the thickness of $0.48\mu$m, which shows that entire buffer layer is depleted under built-in conditions \cite{Neamen2007}.
