\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:5.21}
x_P=\biggl[\biggl(\frac{2\epsilon_sV_{bi}}{q}\biggr)\biggl(\frac{N_d}{N_b}\biggr)\biggl(\frac{1}{N_d+N_b}\biggr)\biggr]^{1/2}~.
\end{equation}

Optimization was carried out using an objective function whose details are given elsewhere \cite{Riaz2016}. Optimized variables of Eq. \ref{Eq:5.12} are listed in Table \ref{Tab:5.2}. RMS errors for experimental and simulated $I-V$ characteristics, as a function of biasing voltages, are given in Table \ref{Tab:5.3}. Whereas, observed and simulated $I-V$ characteristics are shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:5.1}.

Table \ref{Tab:5.3} shows that average RMS error for the $I-V$ characteristics of Fig. \ref{Fig:5.1} is $2.3341\times10^{-3}$. Such a small magnitude of error demonstrates the validity of Eq. \ref{Eq:5.12}. It can be seen from Fig. \ref{Fig:5.1} that the device under discussion offers high resistance in its linear region of operation. This could be associated with relatively high values of $R_S$ and $R_D$  caused by the combination of contact resistance, $R_C$ and bulk hesitance, $R_B$. Since $R_B$ is a doping dependent variable and for a given doping, a relatively high value of $R_S$ and  $R_D$ can then be associated with a high value of $R_C$, which is fabrication dependent and may vary from process to process. Since the chosen device has $L_g$ = 0.4$\mu$m, it was therefore, obvious that this device will have short channel effects and the same are visible from the output characteristics shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:5.1} wherein, the device is presenting a considerable high value of $g_d$ and also the performance of Schottky barrier gate is deteriorating with increasing values of $V_{ds}$ and $V_{gs}$ \cite{Ahmed1997, Ahmed2001}. Such devices do not comply to standard square law expressions for their output characteristics, in the saturation region of operation, and therefore, a non-linear expression of the form shown by Eq. \ref{Eq:5.12} is required to simulate $I-V$ characteristics of such devices.
